Soup dumplings are freshly made on premises. Tried take out for the first time. It was pretty good. Must have the soup dumplings pork or pork w crab meat. Crab meat one is a bit sweeter but still good. And must try the stir fried udon. Delicious

The udon plate at this place has been one of my favorite, if not just the one. It's a good portion and well balanced between meat, veggies and noodles, perfect. The dumplings are so flavorful and basically, all the items that we have tried didn't disappoint.
This place is back open for take out! Yay!!! How I missed their soup dumplings! Scallion pancakes! Everything is great!

I found out about this place from my brother in law so we gave it a try. My first impression was positive as it was really bright, clean and the decor was very inviting. I liked how the menus had lots of pictures of the dishes.  We ordered the crab soup dumplings which is a must have item. It was absolutely delicious and paired very well with their sweet vinegar. Just as good if not better than Joe Shanghai's but in a much more convenient location in Brooklyn.  The pork belly was really tender and flavorful. Perfect to eat with a bowl of white rice. The sweet spare ribs packed a lot of flavor as well.  Overall the price was right and the food was great. We'll definitely be coming back here many more times as we saw a couple of dishes other folks ordered that looked really good.  UPDATE 2:  So good we had to come back for the soup dumplings and try the other items.  It definitely did not disappoint at all!  Grandma's Pork was braised so perfectly tender and oodles of flavor!  The spicy chicken was on point!  The right amount of savory, spicy and the perfect amount of crispness.  The scallion noodles was another star dish.  So simple yet done amazingly!  The spare ribs was a bit dry the first time but they redeemed themselves the 2nd time and it was much more juicy this time around.  I actually dipped some of the spicy chicken in the spare rib sauce :)  The chicken in spicy oil is sooo good. Literally every piece was the perfect dark meat and no bones!  Got some soup dumplings for take away it tastes just as great. Remember to get the delicious sweet vinegar to go!  UPDATE3:  The general tsos tasted really good but the texture wasn't crispy enough. I prefer the breading to be very crispy.  The golden shrimp had a nice salted egg flavor but I would prefer it within the shell unless it was made crispier.  The scallion pancake is cooked perfectly. Light and delicious!  UPDATE4:  Wuxi ribs - braised to the point where the meat falls off the bone. Tastes similar to grandma's pork without all the fat.  I really like a edible cartilage.  Take out tastes just as good as eating in!!

The one dish that is always overlooked for vegetarian is the pickled cabbage  with tofu skin.  It is very delicious.  I always order it everytime I go to a Shanghai or Taiwanese restaurant.  The service was amazing especially if you have children.  The waitress were very attentive to children.  Very family friendly except no toys here. Did I also mention BYOB!!

This place was absolutely incredible! I get my steak done medium-rare and they did a fabulous job! Even the little buns were delectable. Especially with the vinegar - yum!! The Chinese dishes also rock. The Steak I got basically melted in my mouth. Which says so much about then amazing steaks. It’s also very inexpensive, totally worth every penny. Staff is very knowledgeable about the meats and everything else on the menu. Can't wait to go back someday!

We came all the way from Queens to give it a try since it's one of the best Shanghai soup dumplings restaurant in NY as the newspaper says, and as you can see the photo i post here, we finish all the dishes on the table, and I can say Mr Bun is the BEST!! We love everything here and will definitely come back again!! 5 stars recommend XD
Typical chinese food with reasonable price. Good service, food is very delicious as well.
Very delicious, service is very good, very authentic Chinese Shanghainese cuisine.
The best Chinese restaurant in Brooklyn. Highly recommended. You can find whatever you want from here.
Amazing soup dumplings, great service, kind staff, and very affordable prices. Highly recommended!

A hike from Astoria but the soup dumplings were on point. Skin was not too dense, just thin enough and a good amount of meat, great job, Mr Bun! Wished I had that ginger to go with it though. Maybe I should have asked. Ha Also, had scallion pancake and love the crispness of it. The steam pan fried buns were good but not salty enough for me. Beef udon yummy but needed more veggies. Three cup chicken was good, had the flavors but not soaked into the chicken enough.
Just came here with my wife.  She definitely approves, and me too!  Amazing food, decor, and service.  Will be coming back soon!  Soup dumplings were the best I've ever had.

It’s an ok dumpling place in Brooklyn but not close to quality of Kung Fu Xiao Luong Bao in Queens. The scallions pancake with beef was mediocre and the fried pork buns was overpriced! Everywhere else I go there’s 6 buns. Here they give you 4. Not a bad place but they can definitely do better. I do like the beef LO mein. The general tso was mediocre as well.

The food here is pretty decent, and the prices are not bad. their pork buns are really good and their scallion pancakes are really flakey but could use a bit more salt. And they have stirfry rice cake!! *If you spend over $25 I believe you get a free order of soup dumplings! 😊😋

Terrible customer service. Accidentally pressed order on ubereats, then instantly called the restaurant to cancel the order and they proceed to tell me the food's already done. How does that make any sense. I will never patronize this place again. And also the rice cake beef was dry.

If you plan to dine in the restaurant, be ready to pay extra big tips or the waitress or waiter will come chasing after you. Foods was ok but the service was bad. The waitress confronted to us as we are leaving, saying we did not pay enough tips, customers are mandated to pay at least 18% tips. I stated tip are pay based on the quality of the waitress and waiter service. I have to ask a couple of time for everything and the waitress gave me a nasty attitude when I asked. I also told them I have take out where tips should not be included since there’s taxes. The waitress start to argue and told other staff these customer did not pay enough tips. I guess we are black listed and will be expecting spits at our foods if we do go back.

First time coming here and already the dishes are amazing! It's something that you have to try to understand, no wonders can describe it. The place itself is interesting, covered in familiar anime and a place for figurines. It's really an interesting thing to see, especially for those visiting NY and want to try something local. I would recommend this place! 👍🏻

So, the first thing that catches your eyes is the crazy One Piece decor. What’s with the amount of One Piece restaurants on 86th recently? But, besides that, the food is pretty decent for Shanghainese.  The owner, staff, and chef seem to actually be Cantonese, but they do make a pretty decent xiaolongbao and beef wrap. Most of the stir fried noodles are also tasty with a subtle hint of wok hei or that wok flavor that’s coveted in good stir fry. Not enough to actually be great, but just hints at being there. They have an amazing egg yolk crusted shrimp (that’s actually cantonese dish) that I highly recommend when coming here.  The mapo tofu wasn’t too good, didn’t have much flavor besides a mala sting.  For dessert, definitely try the fried pumpkin mochi filled with red bean. So tasty and decadent.  Decent addition to the 86th street food scene and I enjoy eating here for sure.
Twice I order takeout and the food was fantastic. Highly recommend fried buns comes in order of four. Service is courteous. Clean establishment.

Food is not bad. Price is decent as well. Was sort of surprised that the soupy dumplings only came in 6, that cost $5.95. Quite costly if you break it down. Service is great. Like that the restaurant is bright and spacious. Tables are not jammed back to back like other restaurants.

Lovely local neighborhood gem, serving up great Shanghai cuisine.  Everything is reasonably priced and delicious. Soup dumplings is what they are famous for and a great tasting menu. Snacks, appetizers, and even entrees are great for sharing, the portions are decent. My favorite item was the dumplings of course, the drunken chicken, scallion pancakes, and the crab rice cakes. The red bean Pumpkin dessert was excellent as well, sweet but not overly sweet. Served hot. Yummy.  Came on an early Saturday night, 6pm, but dinner rush happened at 7pm and it was easily a packed house. Reservation suggested.

Absolutely delicious. The soup dumplings were full of soup with amazing flavors. The pancake with beef is a must order. The bun (bao) was also surprisingly juicy. I've never had a bun like this even in Chinatown Shanghai restaurants. Will definitely come back again.

It’s a very cute place for handing out with friends and family members, also for my kids. Soup dumplings, scallions pancakes are all good. Waiters are all good and very patient to my baby. Will come again and again!

We ordered the crab meat soup dumplings and pork soup dumplings, both are excellent! Soup is fresh and meat is tender. Besides, we tried stir fried shredded beef with bamboo shoot and beef tripe. As some one who is from Sichuan and has high standard about spicy food, I would honestly say they are really good with the flavor and know how to make it. It's definately nowy top 3 restaurant in New York to visit.

The best Shanghai soup dumpling is finally available in 86th street, Bensonhurst. I ordered a few dishes and they were all very delicious. The interior is very cozy and a lot of cute cartoon characters on the wall. Ordering is super easy. The staff members are efficient and fast. I’d love to go back again for more dumplings.
